🗂️ Core Exam Domains
SEC699 structures content into five progressive sections, which map directly to the GPTE exam domains: SANS Institute

Section 1 — Purple Team Foundations & Tooling
Section one lays the foundational requirements for successful adversary emulation and purple teaming. Since SEC699 is an advanced course, it goes in-depth on several key tools and teaches students how to further extend and customize them for real-world use. SANS Institute
Topics covered:

Purple team methodology and program design
Adversary emulation frameworks (MITRE ATT&CK, TIBER, CBEST)
C2 frameworks: Covenant and Caldera (setup, configuration, plugin development)
Building adversary emulation infrastructure with Ansible, Docker, Terraform
Extending and customizing offensive tooling


Section 2 — Initial Access Techniques & Detection
The course teaches students to execute complex initial access techniques with a strong emphasis on their corresponding detection strategies. SANS Institute
Topics covered:

Phishing and spear-phishing emulation
Application whitelisting bypasses
Macro-based and fileless malware delivery
OPSEC-aware payload staging
Email gateway and EDR detection logic
SIGMA rule writing for initial access TTPs


Section 3 — Lateral Movement & Privilege Escalation
Section three covers lateral movement and privilege escalation techniques in depth, paired with detection strategies for each method. SANS Institute
Topics covered:

Pass-the-Hash / Pass-the-Ticket
Kerberoasting & AS-REP Roasting
Token impersonation and credential theft
Cross-forest attacks (Kerberos delegation abuse)
Active Directory misconfigurations and ACL abuse
Detection via Windows Event Logs, Sysmon, and EDR telemetry


Section 4 — Persistence, Exfiltration & Stealth Techniques
The course covers delivering advanced attacks including application whitelisting bypasses, cross-forest attacks (abusing delegation), and stealth persistence strategies. Contentstack
Topics covered:

Registry, scheduled task, and WMI-based persistence
DLL hijacking and COM hijacking
C2 channel obfuscation and HTTPS beaconing
Data staging and exfiltration techniques
Defense evasion: AMSI bypass, ETW tampering, log clearing


Section 5 — Threat Actor Emulation Plans & Detection Engineering
Building SIGMA rules to detect advanced adversary techniques is a key capstone skill tested in the exam. Contentstack The detection cycle is circular, accounting for alert verification, alert bypass, false-positive tuning, and procedural variance testing — all of which are exam-relevant skills. SANS Institute
Topics covered:

Building full adversary emulation plans (APT-28, APT-34, Turla, etc.)
MITRE ATT&CK Navigator mapping and gap analysis
Detection-as-code and SIGMA rule authoring
Measuring detection coverage and security control validation
Purple team reporting and feedback loops to blue team
Using Caldera to automate and repeat emulation campaigns


🛠️ Key Tools You're Expected to Know
SEC699 immerses students in adversary emulation using tools like Covenant and Caldera, with 60% of course time being hands-on lab work across 29 labs. Contentstack
The exam expects hands-on familiarity with: Covenant C2, Caldera, SIGMA rules, Sysmon, MITRE ATT&CK Navigator, Atomic Red Team, Ansible/Terraform for range deployment, and Windows AD attack tooling (Rubeus, BloodHound, Mimikatz context).

👤 Who Is It For?
SEC699 is designed for IT security professionals who want to develop skills in automation, tooling, planning, and executing complex adversary scenarios, progressively building expertise from foundational concepts to intricate purple team techniques, culminating in comprehensive threat actor emulation plans. Contentstack
Ideal candidates: SOC analysts, red teamers, detection engineers, incident responders, and threat hunters who already have foundational offensive/defensive experience (SEC599/GDAT is a natural prerequisite).
